-- Qatar Stocks Rise to Two-Year High on Global Growth Optimism, Oil Gains
-- B y   Z a h r a   H a n k i r
-- 2010-11-04T12:00:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-04/qatar-stocks-rise-to-three-week-high-on-global-growth-optimism-oil-gains.html
Qatar  shares  rallied to the highest
level in more than two years, leading gains in Gulf markets,
after the Federal Reserve expanded measures to boost the world’s
largest economy, lifting demand for global shares and crude oil.  Qatar National Bank,  the Persian Gulf country’s biggest
lender by assets, surged to the highest in more than five years
and  Commercial Bank of Qatar  increased 1.3 percent. The  QE Index 
climbed 1.3 percent to 7,903.32 at the 12:30 p.m. close in Doha,
bringing this week’s gain to 1.3 percent. Bahrain’s  gauge 
increased 0.4 percent and the  Bloomberg GCC 200 Index  added 0.9
percent, the most since Sept. 14.  “Qatar’s market is reflecting what happened globally,”
said  Haissam Arabi,  chief executive officer of Gulfmena
Alternative Investments in Dubai. “It will continue an upward
trend.” The Gulf emirate’s measure has  jumped 14 percent  this
year.  The Fed yesterday said it would buy $600 billion in
Treasury securities through next June in a bid to further reduce
long-term borrowing costs and keep prices from falling. Policy
makers said they will “adjust the program as needed to best
foster maximum employment and price stability.” Emerging market
and developing nations’ stocks rose as the quantity of purchases
exceeded the expectations of economists.  The  MSCI Asia Pacific Index  rose as much as 1.8 percent and
Europe’s  STOXX Europe 600 Index  increased 1.3 percent. The  MSCI
Emerging Markets Index  gained for a sixth day, advancing 1.1
percent. The majority of economists surveyed by Bloomberg News
expected the Fed would add at least $500 billion to the
financial system.  Oil Gains  Crude for December delivery rose as much 1.6 percent to
$86.05 a barrel in electronic trading on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. The six nations of the Gulf Cooperation Council, made
up of the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
Oman and Bahrain, supply about a fifth of the world’s oil.  Qatar National jumped 1.7 percent to 169.2 riyals, the
highest since September 2005. Commercial Bank of Qatar, the
country’s second-biggest lender by assets, advanced to 83.9
riyals, the highest since Oct. 20.  Dubai’s  DFM General Index  gained 0.2 percent after earlier
losing as much as 1.2 percent while Abu Dhabi’s  measure  slipped
0.4 percent, dropping for the eighth day. The  Kuwait Stock
Exchange Index  declined 0.1 percent and Oman’s  MSM30 Index 
gained 0.3 percent. Saudi Arabia’s market was closed for the
weekend.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Zahra Hankir  in Dubai at 
 zhankir@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
